The start symbol S can produce strings only by one of the following binary rules  

1. S → NT4 NT8  
2. S → NT4 NT11  
3. S → NT1 NT2  

Hence any derivation of the whole string must begin with the left‐hand constituent NT4 or NT1.

• NT4 can be a single terminal (t0, t5 or t7) or it can be built as NT14 NT7, where NT14 itself begins with either t5 or t2 (because NT14 → NT3 NT4 and NT3 only produces t5 or t2).  
  Consequently every string derived from NT4 must start with t0, t5 or t7.  
  The given string starts with t10, so it cannot begin with NT4.

• NT1 can be a single terminal t8 or can be produced in three binary ways:

  – NT1 → NT9 NT13  (first symbol t10)  
  – NT1 → NT12 NT8  (first symbol is whatever NT12 produces, never t10)  
  – NT1 → NT7 NT14  (first symbol t10)

  The only possibilities that let NT1 begin with the required first symbol t10 are the rules using NT9 or NT7 on the left.  
  Both of these rules create at least two terminals before they can reach the partner NT2 in S → NT1 NT2.  
  Checking all length-2 substrings of the given string, no pair beginning with t10 (positions 1-2) is generated by any non-terminal at all: the pair (t10 t1) corresponds to the symbol sequence (NT9, NT10), and there is no rule with that right-hand side.  
  Thus no non-terminal – in particular neither NT1 nor anything that could grow into NT1 – derives the substring “t10 t1…”.

Because the string cannot start with NT4 and cannot start with NT1, none of the three productions for S can match the given input. Therefore the grammar cannot generate the string.

No

The start-symbol S can expand only in one of the following three ways:

1. S → NT4 NT8  
2. S → NT4 NT11  
3. S → NT1 NT2  

In every derivation the first terminal of the produced string must come from the first non-terminal of the chosen rule (NT4 or NT1).  
Therefore the only question is: can NT4 or NT1 ever generate a string whose very first terminal symbol is t4?

Examine NT4:  
NT4 → 't0' | 't5' | 't7' | NT14 NT7  
• The single-terminal alternatives never yield t4.  
• If NT4 → NT14 NT7, the first symbol is the first symbol produced by NT14.  
  NT14 → NT3 NT4, so the first symbol is the first symbol produced by NT3.  
  NT3 → 't5' | 't2' | NT7 NT1.  
  – 't5' and 't2' are not t4.  
  – In NT7 NT1 the first symbol is produced by NT7.  
    NT7 can start with 't0' or 't10' (its two terminal rules) or with NT9/NT11/NT12/NT1, none of which can start with t4 (their terminal rules are t0, t10, t9, t3, t5, t2, t7, t8, etc.).  
So NT4 can never generate a string whose leading terminal is t4.

Examine NT1:  
NT1 → 't8' | NT9 NT13 | NT12 NT8 | NT7 NT14  
• The direct terminal rule is t8, not t4.  
• In NT9 NT13 the first symbol comes from NT9, whose terminal rules are t0, t10, t9.  
• In NT12 NT8 the first symbol comes from NT12. NT12 starts with NT8 or NT3, whose leading terminals are t0, t5, or t2.  
• In NT7 NT14 the first symbol comes from NT7, whose leading terminals are t0 or t10 (same reasoning as above).  
Hence NT1 also can never start with t4.

Because neither NT4 nor NT1 can derive a string beginning with the terminal symbol t4, none of S’s three alternatives can produce a sentence whose first token is t4. Consequently the given string (whose first token is t4) is not in the language generated by the grammar.

No

For any derivation in a context-free grammar, the first terminal symbol of the generated string must come from the leftmost non-terminal in the start production and from the leftmost branch at every subsequent step.

Start symbol S has only three binary productions:

1. S → NT4 NT8
2. S → NT4 NT11
3. S → NT1 NT2

Therefore the first terminal of every sentence in the language must be produced by NT4 (rules 1 & 2) or by NT1 (rule 3).

• NT1 has a single terminal production NT1 → ‘t8’; hence NT1 can only begin a string with t8.

• NT4’s possible starting terminals are obtained from

 – NT4 → ‘t0’ | ‘t5’ | ‘t7’  
 – NT4 → NT14 NT7, with NT14 → NT3 NT4.  
   NT3 can start with ‘t5’, ‘t2’ or any symbol that NT7 can start with.  
   NT7 can start with ‘t0’, ‘t10’, ‘t9’, ‘t3’, or ‘t8’ (from its various productions).

Thus NT4 can begin with at most { t0, t2, t3, t5, t7, t8, t9, t10 }.

Neither NT1 nor NT4 can ever begin a string with t4.

The string we need to generate begins with t4. Since no derivation from S can produce a string whose first symbol is t4, the given string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol S has three possibilities:

1. S → NT4 NT8  
2. S → NT4 NT11  
3. S → NT1 NT2  

Each of the non-terminals on the right–hand sides is part of a strongly-connected cluster of recursive rules that can keep appending further constituents before finally finishing with an optional single-terminal rule.  Concretely:

• NT7 is left-recursive (NT7 → NT9 NT7 | NT11 NT6 | NT12 NT9 | … | ‘t0’ | ‘t10’).  
  Because NT9 can itself yield ‘t0’, ‘t9’ or ‘t10’, NT7 can generate an arbitrary string made of t0/t9/t10 and then stop.

• NT4 can call NT7 (NT4 → NT14 NT7;  NT14 → NT3 NT4) and NT3 yields ‘t5’; thus NT4 can freely add any amount of material coming from NT7 and can also insert ‘t5’ whenever it recycles through NT14.  Consequently NT4 can output any combination of the terminals {t0,t5,t7,t9,t10} in any order and length.

• NT1 can terminate with ‘t8’, but it is also recursive through rules such as NT1 → NT9 NT13 and NT1 → NT7 NT14.  Via NT13 it obtains ‘t4’, ‘t2’, ‘t6’, and via the NT7/NT14 loop it can append all the symbols that NT7 and NT3 can already make.  Therefore NT1 can yield arbitrary strings that in particular may, but need not, contain ‘t8’.

• NT5, NT6, NT8, NT11, NT12 and NT13 are mutually recursive with the same kind of structure, and NT0 and NT2 are built out of pairs of those non-terminals (e.g. NT2 → NT2 NT4 | NT0 NT0 | ‘t2’ | ‘t5’ | ‘t7’).  As a result, NT2 can generate every terminal symbol except ‘t1’ and ‘t6’; those two are irrelevant because they never appear in the target string.

Because all three right-hand non-terminals of S (NT4, NT8, NT11 and NT1, NT2) are able—through the mutually-recursive web of rules sketched above—to produce arbitrarily long strings over precisely the set of terminals that occurs in the test string (t0, t2, t3, t4, t5, t7, t8, t9), we can always divide the 28-token string at some position, hand the left part to the first child and the right part to the second child, and expand the two children independently until the required sequence of terminals is obtained.

Hence a legal derivation of

t0 t7 t0 t9 t0 t2 t9 t4 t9 t5 t0 t0 t2 t8 t8 t9 t2 t0 t7 t8 t2 t9 t3 t2 t0 t0 t7 t5

exists in the grammar.

Yes
